<div id="review_3801967437" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3801967437" />
    <a title="Tejaswini" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/50102631-tejaswini"><img alt="Tejaswini" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577441503p2/50102631.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3801967437?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tejaswini" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tejaswini" href="/user/show/50102631-tejaswini">Tejaswini</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3801967437" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14152079865146178851">Tomo sets off her journey from Fukushima to Tokyo with her six year old daughter Etsuko to Kin&apos;s house who were once their neighbours. On the pretext of meeting &amp; spending time with Kin &amp; her daughter, Tomo secretly carries the burden of task entrusted by her husband Yukitomo Shirakawa. Tomo hesitantingly reveals her real motto behind her visit &amp; seeks Kin in finding out an &apos;inexpirenced&apos; beautiful girl as a second women to the Shirkawa household. Thus Tomo brings 15 year old Suga without her kn</span>
  <span id="freeText14152079865146178851" style="display:none">Tomo sets off her journey from Fukushima to Tokyo with her six year old daughter Etsuko to Kin's house who were once their neighbours. On the pretext of meeting &amp; spending time with Kin &amp; her daughter, Tomo secretly carries the burden of task entrusted by her husband Yukitomo Shirakawa. Tomo hesitantingly reveals her real motto behind her visit &amp; seeks Kin in finding out an 'inexpirenced' beautiful girl as a second women to the Shirkawa household. Thus Tomo brings 15 year old Suga without her knowledge to Shirakawa's home forever as a concubine.<br /><br />'The waiting years' by Fumiko Enchi is a three generational family saga of Shirakawa household. Yukitomo is a high headed government official next to Governor of the province. He is a person full of arrogance, dominance &amp; lust. More than anything, to camaflague his lecherous deeds , he registers his dearly concubines who are young enough to be his daughters as the adopted daughters.<br /><br />Tomo is a strong character in the story who strives ever to withled the cracking repute of Shirakawa's by clogging the seepages of 'immorality' from leaking out. She turns a blind eye to all ongoing unchaste relationships in the family; though Suga &amp; Yumi had snatched her husband &amp; thrown away far from her reach she maintains sugary bonds with them overlooking the tinge of emerging jealousy. She worries about the family's lineage with her ill tempered son Michimasa &amp; licentious daughter in law Miya. Yet Tomo never tires of protecting the bed rock of family from trumbling down into pieces.<br /><br />Enchi's writing is layered &amp; constructive bringing all due charm to the book. She has depicted yester years' Japan with social &amp; political vignettes of the period. Enchi has given importance to both Suga &amp; Yumi who long for marital &amp; mother lives.<br /><br />Reading Shirakawa's family saga, Enchi mirrors reality wiping off the hazed layer on the reflection of proclaimed Japanese authorities.She has put forth the shadowed hind views of the higher rung families where the blotched intuitions are concelaed with bamboo blinds; where gloomy atmosphere is outshined by the gleaming exteriors &amp; where feebly held family ties are surprisingly contrast to the intricately furnished mohaghany interiors.</span>
