<div id="review_3759658417" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3759658417" />
    <a title="Angelina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/267307-angelina"><img alt="Angelina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1187360450p2/267307.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3759658417?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angelina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angelina" href="/user/show/267307-angelina">Angelina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780870111594" href="/book/show/3640066-the-waiting-years">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/267307-angelina?shelf=female-writers">female-writers</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/267307-angelina?shelf=library">library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/267307-angelina?shelf=asian">asian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/267307-angelina?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3759658417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1916303910977865369">3.5 stars. <br/><i>&quot;Was it possible, then, that everything that she had lived for was vain and profitless? No: she shook her head in firm rejection of the idea. Her world was a precarious place, a place where one groped one&apos;s way through the gloom; where everything one&apos;s hand touched was colorless, hard and cold; where the darkness seemed to stretch endlessly ahead. Yet at the end of it all a brighter world surely lay waiting, like the light when one finally emerges from a tunnel. If it were not there w</i></span>
  <span id="freeText1916303910977865369" style="display:none">3.5 stars. <br /><i>"Was it possible, then, that everything that she had lived for was vain and profitless? No: she shook her head in firm rejection of the idea. Her world was a precarious place, a place where one groped one's way through the gloom; where everything one's hand touched was colorless, hard and cold; where the darkness seemed to stretch endlessly ahead. Yet at the end of it all a brighter world surely lay waiting, like the light when one finally emerges from a tunnel. If it were not there waiting, then nothing made sense."</i> (p. 190)<br /><br />While reading this book I kept wondering what the title meant and what the original title in Japanese was. It sure is a mostly sad (and infuriating) book to read, set in the Meiji era and covering several decades before WWI. It's a time of strong patriarchy when women have little power over their lives and the choices they make, even less so when their families are poor. They are often treated as (valuable) assets that can be sold or exchanged depending on the circumstances. <br />The women in the novel and especially the central character, Tomo, spend their lives waiting for better times while waiting on their husbands or masters, always knowing that they can be easily replaced. <br />Enchi is an objective and fierce narrator that doesn't offer judgement but also doesn't shy away from calling things what they are by drawing complex female characters. Her opinion on the matters is quite clear. As for the light at the end of the tunnel, we can see it far off in the distance(at least Tomo's daughter seems to have drawn a better marriage card) but even today it hasn't arrived 100% percent. <br /><br />* * * * * <br />A few more quotes:<br /><br /><i>"It was wicked. They were giving a girl still of an age to be playing with dolls to a man a full two dozen years her senior, an elderly roue who had already tasted all world's pleasures. The girl's parents were a party to the whole proceedings. Even if they had nod given her to be his mistress, they could never have got enough money to keep the family going without handing over her fresh young body in exchange."<br /><br />"Something indefinable in her appearance began to betray the painful awareness that her body had been sold for money."<br /><br />"Objectively speaking, there were any number of prominent and distinguished men in society today who had cast off their wives of many years like worn-out slippers and sent them back to their homes in the country, taking as their recognized spouses attractive women risen from the ranks of apprentice geishas or geishas."</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="1916303910977865369" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


